{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-90f99a447952f991", "type": "tool_result", "content": "m{aug}} BSFiLM Encoder BSFiLM Encoder FiLM FiLM Projection Projection 𝐞 orig \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{orig}} 𝐞 aug \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{aug}} 𝐦 1 \\mathbf{m}_{1} 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{2} 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 ∈ ℝ 512 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{512} FX Chain Generator cross-attn [BOS] vocals sox_comp thresh 0.30 ratio 0.50 ⋯ \\cdots predicted [BOS] vocals sox_comp thresh 0.28 ratio 0.45 ⋯ \\cdots ground truth teacher forcing ℒ CE \\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{CE}} effect tokens value tokens shared weights Figure 1 : StemFX system overview. Original and target stems pass through the shared BSFiLM Encoder to produce embeddings, projected into conditioning vectors 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2} that the Transformer decoder attends to via cross-attention. The FX Chain Generator is trained with teacher forcing and cross-entropy loss against the next ground-truth token. 3 Method 3.1 Framework Overview and Problem Formulation Figure 1 illustrates the StemFX architecture. The framework jointly trains a BSFiLM Encoder and a Transformer-based FX Chain Generator end-to-end. The encoder maps both the original and augmented stems into conditioning vectors that summarize the mixing style difference, and the generator autoregressively predicts the tokenized FX chain that was applied. By treating FX chain prediction as a sequence generation problem, StemFX supports variable-length chains with arbitrary effects. We formalize the task as follows. Let 𝐱 ∈ ℝ 8 × T \\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{8\\times T} denote a set of four source-separated stereo stems (vocals, bass, drums, other) at 44.1 kHz. Given an original input 𝐱 orig \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{orig}} and a target 𝐱 aug \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{aug}} augmented with a known FX chain, the goal is to predict the per-stem FX chain ℱ \\mathcal{F} that transforms 𝐱 orig \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{orig}} to match 𝐱 aug \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{aug}} . Each stem’s chain is an ordered list of effect–parameter pairs: ℱ s = [ ( f 1 , 𝜽 1 ) , ( f 2 , 𝜽 2 ) , … , ( f N s , 𝜽 N s ) ] , s ∈ 𝒮 \\mathcal{F}_{s}=\\bigl[(f_{1},\\boldsymbol{\\theta}_{1}),\\,(f_{2},\\boldsymbol{\\theta}_{2}),\\,\\ldots,\\,(f_{N_{s}},\\boldsymbol{\\theta}_{N_{s}})\\bigr],\\quad s\\in\\mathcal{S} (1) where 𝒮 = { vocals , bass , drums , other } \\mathcal{S}=\\{\\text{vocals},\\text{bass},\\text{drums},\\text{other}\\} , f i f_{i} is a specific effect name (e.g., sox_compand ), 𝜽 i \\boldsymbol{\\theta}_{i} its parameters (e.g., threshold, ratio), and N s N_{s} varies per stem. We concatenate the 4 per-stem FX chains into the full chain ℱ = { ℱ s } s ∈ 𝒮 \\mathcal{F}=\\{\\mathcal{F}_{s}\\}_{s\\in\\mathcal{S}} , which is serialized into a single token sequence 𝐲 \\mathbf{y} for autoregressive prediction (Section 3.3 ). 3.2 BSFiLM Encoder The encoder maps the 8-channel input 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} to a mixing style embedding 𝐞 ∈ ℝ 512 \\mathbf{e}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{512} , following a multi-band CNN design inspired by Kim et al. [ 11 ] and adapted for representation learning with FiLM conditioning. Each of the 8 channels is transformed into a log-mel spectrogram with n fft = 2048 n_{\\mathrm{fft}}=2048 , hop = 512 =512 , and n mels = 80 n_{\\mathrm{mels}}=80 , yielding shape ( B , 8 , 80 , T ′ ) (B,8,80,T^{\\prime}) . The frequency axis is divided into overlapping sub-bands of 20 mel bins with 10-bin overlap. Each sub-band is processed by an independent 2-layer CNN with 7 × 7 7{\\times}7 kernels, 32 → \\to 64 channels, batch normalization, and max pooling, producing per-band feature maps. FiLM [ 12 ] injects 64 hand-crafted mixing features into each CNN layer, as detailed in Table 1 . These features are adapted from the Diff-MST [ 2 ] mixing feature set to our four-stem setting, computing dynamics, spectral, stereo, and inter-stem descriptors per stem. A 2-layer MLP generates scale 𝜸 \\boldsymbol{\\gamma} and shift 𝜷 \\boldsymbol{\\beta} parameters: 𝐱 ′ = 𝜸 ⊙ 𝐱 + 𝜷 , ( 𝜸 , 𝜷 ) = MLP ​ ( 𝐟 ) \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime}=\\boldsymbol{\\gamma}\\odot\\mathbf{x}+\\boldsymbol{\\beta},\\quad(\\boldsymbol{\\gamma},\\boldsymbol{\\beta})=\\mathrm{MLP}(\\mathbf{f}) (2) The per-band feature maps are concatenated along the channel axis, flattened across frequency, and temporally pooled via learned attention weights to produce the 512-dimensional embedding (1.79M parameters total). Independent per-band CNNs allow each sub-band to specialize in detecting frequency-specific processing such as band-limited EQ, compression, or de-essing. Table 1 : Hand-crafted mixing features for FiLM conditioning (64 total). Category Feature (formula) /Stem Total Dynamics RMS: 1 T ​ ∑ x c 2 \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{T}\\sum x_{c}^{2}} ( × \\times 2 ch.) 6 24 Crest: 20 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( max ⁡ | x c | RMS c ) 20\\log_{10}\\!\\bigl(\\frac{\\max|x_{c}|}{\\mathrm{RMS}_{c}}\\bigr) ( × \\times 2 ch.) K-weighted loudness ( × \\times 2 ch.): − 0.691 + 10 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( ∑ c G c ⋅ RMS c 2 ) -0.691+10\\log_{10}\\!\\bigl(\\sum_{c}G_{c}\\cdot\\mathrm{RMS}_{c}^{2}\\bigr) Spectral Band energy: E ¯ low , E ¯ mid , E ¯ high \\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{low}},\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{mid}},\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{high}} 5 20 Tilt: ρ ​ ( bin index , E ¯ mel ) \\rho(\\text{bin index},\\,\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{mel}}) Flatness: exp ⁡ ( log ⁡ S ¯ ) / S ¯ \\exp(\\overline{\\log S})\\,/\\,\\bar{S} Stereo ILD: 20 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( RMS L / RMS R ) 20\\log_{10}(\\mathrm{RMS}_{L}/\\mathrm{RMS}_{R}) 3 12 Correlation: ∑ L ~ ​ R ~ / ‖ L ~ ‖ ​ ‖ R ~ ‖ \\sum\\tilde{L}\\tilde{R}\\,/\\,\\|\\tilde{L}\\|\\|\\tilde{R}\\| Mid-side ratio: E side / E mid E_{\\mathrm{side}}/E_{\\mathrm{mid}} Rel. loud. L stem − L mix L_{\\mathrm{stem}}-L_{\\mathrm{mix}} 1 4 Masking σ ​ ( − ( E s − max j ≠ s ⁡ E j ) ) ¯ \\overline{\\sigma\\!\\bigl(-(E_{s}-\\max_{j\\neq s}E_{j})\\bigr)} 1 4 x c x_{c} : waveform of channel c c ; S S : mel spectrogram; E ¯ \\bar{E} : mean energy over time and channels; L ~ , R ~ \\tilde{L},\\tilde{R} : zero-mean left/right channels; E mid = ( ( L + R ) / 2 ) 2 ¯ E_{\\mathrm{mid}}=\\overline{((L{+}R)/2)^{2}} , E side = ( ( L − R ) / 2 ) 2 ¯ E_{\\mathrm{side}}=\\overline{((L{-}R)/2)^{2}} ; σ \\sigma : sigmoid; E s E_{s} : mel energy of stem s s ; G c G_{c} : channel weighting per ITU-R BS.1770. 3.3 FX Chain Tokenization We serialize variable-length, multi-stem FX chains into flat token sequences. The vocabulary of 358 tokens comprises 4 special tokens, 4 stem tokens, 85 effect name tokens, 164 parameter name tokens, and 101 quantized value bins. An example sequence is: [BOS] vocals sox_gain sox_gain_gain_db value_55 sox_compand sox_compand_threshold_db value_30 sox_compand_ratio value_50 ... [SEP] [EOS] Continuous parameter values are normalized to [ 0 , 1 ] [0,1] and quantized to 101 bins. Frequency-domain parameters such as filter cutoffs use log-scale normalization to match perceptual sensitivity, v ^ = ( log ⁡ v − log ⁡ v min ) / ( log ⁡ v max − log ⁡ v min ) \\hat{v}=(\\log v-\\log v_{\\min})/(\\log v_{\\max}-\\log v_{\\min}) , while all other parameters such as gain, ratio, and attack/release times use linear normalization, v ^ = ( v − v min ) / ( v max − v min ) \\hat{v}=(v-v_{\\min})/(v_{\\max}-v_{\\min}) . The vocabulary is extensible; adding a new effect requires only a name token, parameter tokens, and normalization ranges. 3.4 FX Chain Generator Both 𝐱 orig \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{orig}} and 𝐱 aug \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{aug}} pass through the shared BSFiLM Encoder to produce 2 embeddings 𝐞 orig \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{orig}} and 𝐞 aug \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{aug}} . Each embedding is independently projected via a shared projection head consisting of LayerNorm, Linear, ReLU, and Linear layers, producing conditioning vectors 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 ∈ ℝ 512 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{512} that serve as key-value entries for the decoder’s cross-attention. Our paired-embedding design is inspired by AFx-Rep [ 6 ] , which encodes both original and augmented audio to learn effect representations from their paired embeddings. We adopt this paired-input paradigm but replace the classification head with a 6-layer Transformer decoder with d model = 512 d_{\\mathrm{model}}=512 , 8 heads, and FFN dimension 2048. The decoder attends to [ 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 ] [\\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2}] via cross-attention and projects to the full vocabulary via a linear head, predicting all token types in a unified output space. Cross-attention separates audio conditioning from the token sequence, allowing the decoder to query the style information independently at each layer. An alternative is to prepend 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2} as prefix tokens. We leave the comparison of conditioning strategies to future work. 3.5 Training Objective The ground-truth FX chain ℱ \\mathcal{F} is serialized into a token sequence 𝐲 = ( y 1 , … , y L ) \\mathbf{y}=(y_{1},\\ldots,y_{L}) . The decoder is trained with teacher forcing, minimizing cross-entropy at each step. ℒ = ℒ CE = − ∑ t log ⁡ p ​ ( y t ∣ y < t , 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 ) \\mathcal{L}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{CE}}=-\\sum_{t}\\log p(y_{t}\\mid y_{<t},\\,\\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2}) (3) where y < t y_{<t} denotes the ground-truth prefix. The decoder applies a causal mask so that each position attends only to preceding tokens and the conditioning vectors 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2} . Training uses AdamW with learning rate 3 × 10 − 4 3{\\times}10^{-4} , weight decay 0.01, linear warmup over 1000 steps, cosine decay, batch size 64, and gradient clipping at norm 1.0. We train jointly for 60 epochs, approximately 56 GPU hours, on a single NVIDIA RTX 5090 GPU using 10-second audio clips. The full model comprises the BSFiLM Encoder with 1.79M parameters and the 6-layer Transformer decoder with 26.2M parameters, totaling 28.0M parameters. 3.6 Inference At inference time, given a pair of audio inputs (original and target), the encoder produces conditioning vectors 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2} that summarize the mixing style difference. The decoder then autoregressively generates the full token sequence via greedy decoding, predicting effect names, parameter names, and quantized values in a single pass. Unlike generative models that aim to produce a range of plausible variants, our goal is to recover the chain tha", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f9835c4e-283f-497f-8f92-cd81062f89ab", "uuid": "49c5ca08-be8c-4260-b412-4b1f53707479", "timestamp": "2026-07-20T05:56:28.256Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "m{aug}} BSFiLM Encoder BSFiLM Encoder FiLM FiLM Projection Projection 𝐞 orig \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{orig}} 𝐞 aug \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{aug}} 𝐦 1 \\mathbf{m}_{1} 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{2} 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 ∈ ℝ 512 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{512} FX Chain Generator cross-attn [BOS] vocals sox_comp thresh 0.30 ratio 0.50 ⋯ \\cdots predicted [BOS] vocals sox_comp thresh 0.28 ratio 0.45 ⋯ \\cdots ground truth teacher forcing ℒ CE \\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{CE}} effect tokens value tokens shared weights Figure 1 : StemFX system overview. Original and target stems pass through the shared BSFiLM Encoder to produce embeddings, projected into conditioning vectors 𝐦 1 , 𝐦 2 \\mathbf{m}_{1},\\mathbf{m}_{2} that the Transformer decoder attends to via cross-attention. The FX Chain Generator is trained with teacher forcing and cross-entropy loss against the next ground-truth token. 3 Method 3.1 Framework Overview and Problem Formulation Figure 1 illustrates the StemFX architecture. The framework jointly trains a BSFiLM Encoder and a Transformer-based FX Chain Generator end-to-end. The encoder maps both the original and augmented stems into conditioning vectors that summarize the mixing style difference, and the generator autoregressively predicts the tokenized FX chain that was applied. By treating FX chain prediction as a sequence generation problem, StemFX supports variable-length chains with arbitrary effects. We