ls, 32 → \\to 64 channels, batch normalization, and max pooling, producing per-band feature maps. FiLM [ 12 ] injects 64 hand-crafted mixing features into each CNN layer, as detailed in Table 1 . These features are adapted from the Diff-MST [ 2 ] mixing feature set to our four-stem setting, computing dynamics, spectral, stereo, and inter-stem descriptors per stem. A 2-layer MLP generates scale 𝜸 \\boldsymbol{\\gamma} and shift 𝜷 \\boldsymbol{\\beta} parameters: 𝐱 ′ = 𝜸 ⊙ 𝐱 + 𝜷 , ( 𝜸 , 𝜷 ) = MLP ​ ( 𝐟 ) \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime}=\\boldsymbol{\\gamma}\\odot\\mathbf{x}+\\boldsymbol{\\beta},\\quad(\\boldsymbol{\\gamma},\\boldsymbol{\\beta})=\\mathrm{MLP}(\\mathbf{f}) (2) The per-band feature maps are concatenated along the channel axis, flattened across frequency, and temporally pooled via learned attention weights to produce the 512-dimensional embedding (1.79M parameters total). Independent per-band CNNs allow each sub-band to specialize in detecting frequency-specific processing such as band-limited EQ, compression, or de-essing. Table 1 : Hand-crafted mixing features for FiLM conditioning (64 total). Category Feature (formula) /Stem Total Dynamics RMS: 1 T ​ ∑ x c 2 \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{T}\\sum x_{c}^{2}} ( × \\times 2 ch.) 6 24 Crest: 20 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( max ⁡ | x c | RMS c ) 20\\log_{10}\\!\\bigl(\\frac{\\max|x_{c}|}{\\mathrm{RMS}_{c}}\\bigr) ( × \\times 2 ch.) K-weighted loudness ( × \\times 2 ch.): − 0.691 + 10 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( ∑ c G c ⋅ RMS c 2 ) -0.691+10\\log_{10}\\!\\bigl(\\sum_{c}G_{c}\\cdot\\mathrm{RMS}_{c}^{2}\\bigr) Spectral Band energy: E ¯ low , E ¯ mid , E ¯ high \\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{low}},\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{mid}},\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{high}} 5 20 Tilt: ρ ​ ( bin index , E ¯ mel ) \\rho(\\text{bin index},\\,\\bar{E}_{\\mathrm{mel}}) Flatness: exp ⁡ ( log ⁡ S ¯ ) / S ¯ \\exp(\\overline{\\log S})\\,/\\,\\bar{S} Stereo ILD: 20 ​ log 10 ⁡ ( RMS L / RMS R ) 20\\log_{10}(\\mathrm{RMS}_{L}/\\mathrm{RMS}_{R}) 3 12 Correlation: ∑ L ~ ​ R ~ / ‖ L ~ ‖ ​ ‖ R ~ ‖ \\sum\\tilde{L}\\tilde{R}\\,/\\,\\|\\tilde{L}\\|\\|\\tilde{R}\\| Mid-side ratio: E side / E mid E_{\\mathrm{side}}/E_{\\mathrm{mid}} Rel. loud. L stem − L mix L_{\\mathrm{stem}}-L_{\\mathrm{mix}} 1 4 Masking σ ​ ( − ( E s − max j ≠ s ⁡ E j ) ) ¯ \\overline{\\sigma\\!\\bigl(-(E_{s}-\\max_{j\\neq s}E_{j})\\bigr)} 1 4 x c x_{c} : waveform of channel c c ; S S : mel spectrogram; E ¯ \\bar{E} : mean energy over time and channels; L ~ , R ~ \\tilde{L},\\tilde{R} : zero-mean left/right channels; E mid = ( ( L + R ) / 2 ) 2 ¯ E_{\\mathrm{mid}}=\\overline{((L{+}R)/2)^{2}} , E side = ( ( L − R ) / 2 ) 2 ¯ E_{\\mathrm{side}}=\\overline{((L{-}R)/2)^{2}} ; σ \\sigma : sigmoid; E s E_{s} : mel energy of stem s s ; G c G_{c} : channel weighting per ITU-R BS.1770. 3.3 FX Chain Tokenization We serialize variable-length, multi-stem FX chains into flat token sequences. The vocabulary of 358 tokens comprises 4 special tokens, 4 stem tokens, 85 effect name tokens, 164 parameter name tokens, and 101 quantized value bins. An example sequence is: [BOS] vocals sox_gain sox_gain_gain_db value_55 sox_compand sox_compand_threshold_db value_30 sox_compand_ratio value_50 ... [SEP] [EOS] Continuous parameter values are normalized to [ 0 , 1 ] [0,1] and quantized to 101 bins. Frequency-domain parameters such as filter cutoffs use log-scale normalization to match perceptual sensitivity, v ^ = ( log ⁡ v − log ⁡ v min ) / ( log ⁡ v max − log ⁡ v min ) \\hat{v}=(\\log v-\\log v_{\\min})/(\\log v_{\\max}-\\log v_{\\min}) , while all other parameters such as gain, ratio, and attack/release times use linear normalization, v ^ = ( v − v min ) / ( v max − v min ) \\hat{v}=(v-v_{\\min})/(v_{\\max}-v_{\\min}) . The vocabulary is extensible; adding a new effect requires only a name token, parameter tokens, and normalization ranges. 3.4 FX Chain Generator Both 𝐱 orig \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{orig}} and 𝐱 aug \\mathbf{x}^{\\mathrm{aug}} pass through the shared BSFiLM Encoder to produce 2 embeddings 𝐞 orig \\mathbf{e}_{\\mathrm{orig}} 